<problem xml:id="PROBLEMPR-integer">
<title>Find the Pattern</title>
<introduction>
<p>
  <!-- \label{problem:PR-integer} -->
  By custom, differentials are written at the end of each term where
  they appear in a given computation so the Product Rule is usually
  written as
  <me>
  \dx{(xy)}=x(\dx{y})+y(\dx{x}).
  </me>
  But this is just a custom so it is not strictly necessary.  We could
  also use the Product Rule in the form
  <me>
  \dx{(xy)}=x(\dx{y})+(\dx{x})y.
  </me>

</p>
</introduction>
<task  xml:id="PARTProdRulTwice">
<statement>
<p>
    Use the Product Rule twice to show that
    <me> \dx{(xyz)}=xy(\dx{z})+x(\dx{y})z+(\dx{x})yz, </me>
  </p>
</statement>
<hint>
<p>
    The Product Rule requires two factors. But we have three:
      <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, and <m>z</m>. We can fix this with the substitution
      <m>\alpha=yz</m>. Then <m>\dx{(xyz)}=\dx{(x\alpha)}.</m> Now use the
      Product Rule.
</p>
</hint>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 Emulate the computations in <xref ref="PARTProdRulTwice">Part</xref>  to show that.
    <me> \dx{(xyzw)}=xyz(\dx{w})+xy(\dx{z})w+x(\dx{y})zw
      +(\dx{x})yzw.  </me>
  </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 What does the Product Rule look like for
    <m>\dx{(x_1x_2x_3\cdots x_n)}?</m>
  </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task  xml:id="PARTPwrRulPosInt">
<statement>
<p>
 Use the result of part (c) with <m>x_1=x_2=\cdots = x_n =x</m> to
    show that <men  xml:id="EQUATIONPwrRulePosInt">\dx\left(x^n\right)=nx^{n-1}\dx{x}.</men> 
  </p>
</statement>
</task>
</problem>

<p>
 <xref ref="EQUATIONPwrRulePosInt">Equation</xref> is called the <term>Power  Rule for Positive Integers</term>.
</p>
<p>
Let's try out our differentiation rules on a relatively simple
example. We will include every single step so that you can see how the
differentiation rules are used in concert.
</p>
<example xml:id="examp:DiffRulesInConcert1">
<p>
  <!-- \label{examp:DiffRulesInConcert1}  -->
  From the Sum Rule we have,
<me>
\dx\left(5x^6-3x^4+21x^2-7\right)
     =\dx\left(5x^6\right)-\dx\left(3x^4\right)+\dx\left(21x^2\right)-\dx(7).
</me>
Next, the Constant Rule, and  the Constant Multiple Rule give,
<me>
\dx\left(5x^6-3x^4+21x^2-7\right)
     =
    5\dx\left(x^6\right)-3\dx\left(x^4\right)+21\dx\left(x^2\right)-0,
</me> 
and by the Power Rule for Positive Integers we have,
<me>
\dx\left(5x^6-3x^4+21x^2-7\right)
     =
    5\left(6x^5\dx{x}\right)-3\left(4x^3\dx{x}\right)+21\left(2x^1\dx{x}\right)
</me>
<me>
\dx\left(5x^6-3x^4+21x^2-7\right)
     =30x^5\dx{x}-12x^3\dx{x}+42x\dx{x}.
</me>
Finally, factoring out the differential of <m>x</m> gives,
<me> 
   \dx\left(5x^6-3x^4+21x^2-7\right) =\left(30x^5-12x^3+42x\right)\dx{x}.
</me>
</p>
<p>
  Did you notice that the differential <m>\dx{x}</m> appeared in every term
  allowing us to factor it out at the end? When there is only one
  independent variable involved (<m>x</m> in this case) that will
  \emph{always} happen. So it provides an easy way to check your
  computations.
</p>
<p>
  If you end with an expression where the differential of the
  independent variable cannot be factored out then you have made a
  mistake in your computations.  You should find your mistake before
  going on. Or just begin again.
      </p>
</example>

<p>
As you become more skilled you will probably do many of the steps from
<xref ref="EXAMPLEexamp:DiffRulesInConcert1"></xref> in your head.  But for now,
notice how the rules work together and are applied as they are needed.
</p>

<example xml:id="examp:DiffRulesInConcert2">
<p>
  <!-- \label{examp:DiffRulesInConcert2} -->
  Here is another example without all the details spelled out.
  Make sure you see which rule is being invoked at each step.
  <md>
<mrow>
    \dx(\textcolor{red}{(2x+5)}\textcolor{blue}{(3x-7)})\amp =\textcolor{red}{(2x+5)}\textcolor{blue}{\dx(3x-7)}+\textcolor{blue}{(3x-7)}\textcolor{red}{\dx(2x+5)}
</mrow>
<mrow>
    \amp =\textcolor{red}{(2x+5)}(3)\dx{x}+\textcolor{blue}{(3x-7)}(2)\dx{x}
</mrow>
<mrow>
    \amp =(6x+15+6x-14)\dx{x}
</mrow>
<mrow>
    \amp =(12x+1)\dx{x}.
</mrow>
</md>

</p>
</example>




