      <subsubsection>
        <title>The Power  Rule for Positive Integers</title>
        <p>
          Let's try out our differentiation rules on a relatively simple
          example. We will include every single step so that you can see how the
          differentiation rules are used in concert.
        </p>

        <example xml:id="examp:DiffRulesInConcert1">
          <!-- \label{examp:DiffRulesInConcert1}  -->
          <p>

            From the Sum Rule we have,
            <me>
              \dx\left(5x^6-3x^4+21x^2-7\right)
              =\dx\left(5x^6\right)-\dx\left(3x^4\right)+\dx\left(21x^2\right)-\dx(7).
            </me>
            Next, the Constant Rule, and  the Constant Multiple Rule give,
            <me>
              =
              5\dx\left(x^6\right)-3\dx\left(x^4\right)+21\dx\left(x^2\right)-0,
            </me>
            and by the Power Rule for Positive Integers we have,
            <mdn>
              <mrow number="no">
                \amp =
                5\left(6x^5\dx{x}\right)-3\left(4x^3\dx{x}\right)+21\left(2x^1\dx{x}\right)
              </mrow>
              <mrow  xml:id="EQUATIONPowRulPosInt">
                \amp =30x^5\dx{x}-12x^3\dx{x}+42x\dx{x}.
              </mrow>
            </mdn>
            Finally, factoring out the differential of <m>x</m> gives,
            <me>
              \dx\left(5x^6-3x^4+21x^2-7\right) =\left(30x^5-12x^3+42x\right)\dx{x}.
            </me>
          </p>


          <!-- \begin{align*} -->
          <!--   \dx\left(5x^6-3x^4+21x^2-7\right) -->
