<subsubsection xml:id="SUBSUBSECTIONGenPowerRule">
  <title>The General Power Rule</title>
  <p>

    It the title of his <m>1684</m> paper Leibniz claimed that his
    <foreign>Calculus Differentialis</foreign> was
    <pubtitle>`` . . .    Impeded Neither by
    Fractional nor Irrational Quantities,  . . . ''
    </pubtitle>

    But notice that nothing we've done so far allows us to differentiate, say
    <m>y=x^{\sqrt{2}}</m>, since <m>\sqrt{2}</m> is irrational and  cannot be represented as a
    fraction. Having an irrational exponent is a bigger problem than it
    seems to be.
  </p>
  <p>
    Take a moment and ask yourself what an expression like
    <m>x^{\sqrt{2}}</m> could even mean.
  </p>
  <p>
    <!-- \begin{center} -->
    <!--   \begin{minipage}{.85\linewidth} -->
    No! No! No! Wait!
  </p>
  <p>
    Don't keep reading as if we didn't just tell you to
    stop. We're serious. Take a moment and think about this.
    How do you multiply <m>\sqrt{2}</m> copies o/f <m>x</m>
    together? Does that even mean anything? If so, what?
  </p>
  <p>
    We clearly have no way (so far) to interpret the meaning of an
    expression like <m>x^{\sqrt{2}}</m>.  So trying to find its
    differential using the techniques we have is hopeless.  In <xref
    ref="CHAlast-elem-funct">Chapter</xref> we will find a way to give
    meaning to <m>x^{\sqrt{2}}</m> and othe/r such expressions. When we
    do we will find that the Power Rule still works. In the meantime, we
    will assume <em>for now</em> that the Power Rule always works, even
    when the exponent is irrational.
  </p>
  <aside>
    <title>Comment</title>
    <p>
      Actually, we will invent it. Meaning is not something we find, it
      is something we create.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <fact  xml:id="THEOREMGenPowRule">
    <title>The General Power  Rule</title>
    <p>
      Let
      <m>\alpha</m> be any real number. Then
      <men  xml:id="FORMULAGenPowRule">\dx(x^{\alpha})=\alpha x^{\alpha-1}\dx{x}</men>.
    </p>
  </fact>


  <example xml:id="example:QR1">
    <p>
      Suppose we wish to find <m>\dx{y}</m> when <m>y=
      \frac{2-3x^2}{\sqrt{x}}</m>.  Rewriting this slightly we have <m>y=
      \frac{2-3x^2}{\sqrt{x}} = x^{\frac12}\left(2-3x^2\right) =
      2x^{-\frac12}-3x^{\frac32}</m>.  From the General Differentiation
      Rules we have:
      <md> 
        <mrow>
          \dx{y}\amp{} = \dx\left(\frac{2-3x^2}{x^{\frac12}}\right)
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp = \dx\left(2x^{-\frac12}-3x^{\frac32}\right)
        </mrow>
        <mrow> 
          \amp = \left[2\left(-\frac12x^{-\frac32}\dx{x}\right)-3\left(\frac32x^{\frac12}\dx{x}\right)\right]
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp{}=\left(-x^{-\frac32}-\frac92x^{\frac12}\right)\dx{x}.
        </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      Now suppose we have <m>z=1/y=\frac{\sqrt{x}}{2-3x^2}</m>.  Can we
      compute
      <m>\dx{z}</m>?      (Be sure you see why the previous approach won't work.)
    </p>
    <p>

      There are actually two different approaches to this problem that use
      the Product Rule.  The first is to rewrite <m>z</m> as
      <m>x^{\frac12}\inverse{(2-3x^2)}</m> then apply the Product Rule followed
      by the Power Rule.
    </p>
    <p>

      The second approach is to clear the fraction so that
      <m>z(2-3x^2)=\sqrt{x}</m>.  From here we can compute the differential of
      both sides (using the Product Rule on the left side) and solve the
      result for <m>\dx{z}</m>.
    </p>
  </example>
  <problem xml:id="problem:QR1">
    <statement>
      <p>
        <!-- \label{problem:QR1} -->
        Compute <m>\dx\left(\frac{\sqrt{x}}{2-3x^2}\right)</m> by each of the two
        methods indicated in <xref ref="EXAMPLEQR1">Example~\</xref>. Verify that your
        results are equivalent either way.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <p>
    Both of the techniques in <xref ref="EXAMPLEQR1">Example~\</xref> are
    straightforward and can be applied to any fractional
    expression. Because this can become a bit cumbersome we will calculate
    <m>\dx\left(\frac{x}{y}\right)</m> once and for all. This will give us
    a convenient shortcut to handle fractional expressions called the
    Quotient Rule.
  </p>
</subsubsection>
<subsubsection  xml:id="SUBSUBQuotRule"> 
  <title>The Quotient Rule</title>

  <fact  xml:id="THEOREMQuotRule">
    <title>The Quotient Rule</title>
    <p>
      <m>\dx{\left(\dfrac{x}{y}\right)}=\dfrac{y\dx{x}-x\dx{y}}{y^2}.</m>
    </p>
  </fact>
  <problem>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Derive the Quotient Rule, <m>\dx{z}=\dfrac{y\dx{x}-x\dx{y}}{y^2}</m>,
        in two ways:
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          By writing <m>\dx\left(\frac{x}{y}\right)=\dx(x\inverse{y})</m>
          and applying the Product Rule.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          By making the substitution <m>z=\frac{x}{y}</m>, so that
          <m>yz=x</m>. Apply the Product Rule and solve for <m>\dx{z}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </problem>
  <p>
    Applying the Quotient Rule directly to  <xref ref="PROBLEMQR1">Problem</xref> we have

    <md>
      <mrow>
        \dx\left(\frac{\textcolor{blue}{\sqrt{x}}}{\textcolor{red}{2-3x^2}}\right) \amp =\frac{(\textcolor{red}{2-3x^2})\dx\left(\textcolor{blue}{x^{1/2}}\right)-\textcolor{blue}{x^{1/2}} \dx(\textcolor{red}{2-3x^2})}{(\textcolor{red}{2-3x^2})^2}
      </mrow>
      <mrow>          \amp =\frac{(2-3x^2)(\frac12 x^{-1/2})\dx{x}-x^{1/2} (-6x)\dx{x}}{(2-3x^2 )^2}</mrow>
      <mrow>          \amp =\frac{(2-3x^2)(\frac12 x^{-1/2})-x^{1/2} (-6x)}{(2-3x^2 )^2}\dx{x}.
      </mrow>
    </md>
  </p>

